{
  "answer": "**Gaṇapatitattva** contains a ritual prescription for purification (*paṅlukatan*), specifically a rite for Gaṇapati that can be used for exorcism. It involves specific materials such as ivory bamboo with a magical drawing (*rajah*) of Gaṇa, offerings (*bantĕn*) including a white and yellow *ajuman* set and a white crested chicken, water in a copper vessel (*sanku*), Sudhāmala flowers, *pras* and *santun* offerings, and a monetary offering of 1100. The rite concludes with prayers and sprinkling the afflicted place, accompanied by a mantra invoking Gaṇapati.[^1]\n\n**Vīramitrodaya** mentions purificatory rites (*śuddhikarma*) as exceptions to prohibitions on taking earth (e.g., cow urine in the evening twilight), but does not provide explicit prescriptions.[^2]\n\nNo other works in the corpus contain ritual prescriptions for purification.\n\n[^1]: Gaṇapatitattva, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136/01/translation/#p-36c962).\n\n[^2]: Vīramitrodaya, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-dd2c81).",
